Data Quality Audit:

This is conceived as a mean of verifying the reported performance as well as enhancing service monitoring and reporting systems. It reviews the service given, the number of consumers of the service and accuracy of the reporting system.

DOA does not check the quality of services provided but facilitates improvements of the services through usage of the service data generated. Effective programmes with accurate data recording and reporting systems receive the most credit in DQA.

The goal of the Data Quality Audit (DQA) is to assure that management of services and allocation of resources (funding) are based on sound and accurate data. The specific objectives include;

Assess the quality of data accuracy, timeliness of service data and reporting system.

Audit the reported figures given by the institution and estimate the national verification factor (VF), recounted/ reported service data.

Providing practical feedback to health workers on how to improve the quality of reported data.

What is auditing?

Auditing is essentially examination of book of accounts. For example ideally on EPI the book of accounts are the various data collection tools in use ledger books, bin cards, tally and summary sheets and immunization register.

It is an independent examination and expression of opinion on the financial statements of an entity by an appointed auditor. Without independence it is not auditing.

Auditors examine every document which support any transaction in a business e.g. services offered in the health facilities. Auditing covers behaviours of staff, their professional qualifications and how responsible they are in their duties.

Auditing exposes those who are defying the standards: ie
- Qualified nurse or health records and information officers who neglect their duties or

Unqualified staffs dealing with work beyond their scope.

Staff using KEPI fridge as a table, cupboards, vehicles, computers used for personal use.

Some advantages of Auditing
- Able to detect fraud
. Prevention of errors in future

Assessment of routine data quality

Capacity building through findings and recommendations by the audit teams.

What must we do?

Ensure that all reports are available and complete ie tally sheets, ledger books, summary sheets, bin cards, supervisory books for the audit year and current year.

Ensure that the data is properly analysed and accurate.

Proper answers should be available to explain the difference in data submitted since this may affect the verification factor confidence interval.

Ensure the consistency of the data reported and denominators used.

Ensure there is a system monitoring completeness and timeliness of reports at district, provincial and national levels.

Encourage regular written feedback to the health facilities/districts audited.

All reports or summary forms should be properly kept and ready for verification.

The health facilities / districts with missing data in the reports should explain why it is so.

Ensure the retention of all health records for at least ten years (10) as stipulated in the national policy.

What we must not do?

Inflate the health facility or district data or reports

Be fraudulent e.g. same ink, fresh ink

Missing reports should not be re-written - may result in a "zero score"

Keep our offices locked or justify by saying the staff with the key is not on duty.
- Fail or sabotage the DQA verification exercise.

